In [6]:
#Split results and demographics.
demographics = immuno_results[["asord", "sex", "dob", "state"]]
immuno_results = immuno_results.drop(["sex", "dob", "state"], axis=1)

#Split results apart based on immunology test. 
calpro = immuno_results[(immuno_results.atestid == "CCAL") | (immuno_results.atestid == "CAL1")]
lactoferrin = immuno_results[(immuno_results.atestid == "FLF01") | (immuno_results.atestid == "FLF03")]
siga = immuno_results[(immuno_results.atestid == "CSIGA")]

#Rename results columns.
calpro = calpro.rename(columns={'atestid': 'calpro', 'aresult': 'calpro_results'})
lactoferrin = lactoferrin.rename(columns={'atestid': 'lactoferrin', 'aresult': 'lactoferrin_results'})
siga = siga.rename(columns={'atestid': 'siga', 'aresult': 'siga_results'})
In [7]:
#Merge immunology markers together based on order ID. 
imm = calpro.merge(lactoferrin, how='outer', on=["asord", "aodate"]).merge(siga, how='outer', on=["asord", "aodate"])
#Set date columns to datetime object. 
imm.aodate = pd.to_datetime(imm.aodate)
#Sort by date.
imm = imm.sort_values(by='aodate').reset_index(drop=True)
#Drop duplicates.
imm = imm.drop_duplicates('asord')
#Rearrange columns.
imm = imm[["asord", "aodate", "calpro", "calpro_results", "lactoferrin", "lactoferrin_results", "siga", "siga_results"]]

#Clean up and standardize results. 
imm.calpro_results = imm.calpro_results.str.replace("^<", "")

imm.loc[imm.siga_results == "", "siga_results"] = "."

#Calculate the nonparametric MannWhitneyWilcoxon rank-sum test, since data is not normally distributed.
#Determine if calprotectin distribution differs between parasite and non-parasite groups.
z, p_value = stats.ranksums(parasite_positive_calpro.calpro_results, parasite_negative_calpro.calpro_results)
print("The p-value is {}, which is less than 0.05. Therefore the null hypothesis that\n\
the parasite-positive calprotectin results come from the same distribution as the\n\
parasite-negative calprotectin results can be rejected.".format(p_value))

The p-value is 1.4779768614772122e-64, which is less than 0.05. Therefore the null hypothesis that
the parasite-positive calprotectin results come from the same distribution as the
parasite-negative calprotectin results can be rejected.
In [35]:
#Fit Bayesian model of calprotectin results by parasite-positive and parasite-negative groups.

parasite_positive_calpro = parasite_positive_calpro.reset_index(drop=True)
parasite_negative_calpro = parasite_negative_calpro.reset_index(drop=True)
parasite_positive_calpro.calpro_results = parasite_positive_calpro.calpro_results.astype('int')
parasite_negative_calpro.calpro_results = parasite_negative_calpro.calpro_results.astype('int')

cp_neg = parasite_negative_calpro.calpro_results + 0.5
cp_pos = parasite_positive_calpro.calpro_results + 0.5

with pm.Model() as model:
    para_neg_lambda = pm.HalfNormal("para_neg_lambda", sd=0.5)
    calpro_para_neg = pm.Exponential("calpro_para_neg", lam=para_neg_lambda, observed=cp_neg)
    
    para_pos_lambda = pm.HalfNormal("para_pos_lambda", sd=0.5)
    calpro_para_pos = pm.Exponential("calpro_para_pos", lam=para_pos_lambda, observed=cp_pos)
    
    calpro_diff_of_lambdas = pm.Deterministic("calpro_diff_of_lambdas", para_pos_lambda - para_neg_lambda)
    
    calpro_para_neg_mean = pm.Deterministic("calpro_para_neg_mean", 1/para_neg_lambda)
    calpro_para_pos_mean = pm.Deterministic("calpro_para_pos_mean", 1/para_pos_lambda)
    
    calpro_diff_of_means = pm.Deterministic("diff_of_means", calpro_para_neg_mean - calpro_para_pos_mean)
    
    v_params = pm.variational.advi(n=50000)
    trace = pm.variational.sample_vp(v_params, draws=5000)

Applied log-transform to para_neg_lambda and added transformed para_neg_lambda_log to model.
Applied log-transform to para_pos_lambda and added transformed para_pos_lambda_log to model.

In [36]:
#Plot most likely values for the mean calprotectin results 
#for parasite-positive and parasite-negative groups, as well
#as the difference between the means of the two distributions.
pm.plot_posterior(trace[1000:], varnames=["calpro_para_pos_mean", "calpro_para_neg_mean", "diff_of_means"], color='#87ceeb');

The model shows the most likely values and uncertainty in the estimate of the means given the data. Since these are probability distributions (unlike classical confidence intervals), you can say that there is a 95% probability that the difference in means is between 5.2 and 6.4 (g/g). Since this range excludes zero, the parasite-negative group has a significantly higher mean calprotectin level compared to the parasite-positive group. This difference in groups is confirmed by the significant p-value of MannWhitneyWilcoxon rank-sum test above.

#Fit Bayesian model of sIgA results by parasite-positive and parasite-negative groups.

sa_pos = parasite_positive_siga.siga_results
sa_neg = parasite_negative_siga.siga_results

with pm.Model() as model:
    siga_para_neg_lambda = pm.HalfNormal("siga_para_neg_lambda", sd=0.5)
    siga_para_neg = pm.Exponential("siga_para_neg", lam=siga_para_neg_lambda, observed=sa_neg)
    
    siga_para_pos_lambda = pm.HalfNormal("siga_para_pos_lambda", sd=0.5)
    siga_para_pos = pm.Exponential("siga_para_pos", lam=siga_para_pos_lambda, observed=sa_pos)
    
    diff_of_lam = pm.Deterministic("diff_of_lam", siga_para_pos_lambda - siga_para_neg_lambda)
    
    siga_para_neg_mean = pm.Deterministic("siga_para_neg_mean", 1/siga_para_neg_lambda)
    siga_para_pos_mean = pm.Deterministic("siga_para_pos_mean", 1/siga_para_pos_lambda)
    
    diff_of_means = pm.Deterministic("diff_of_means", siga_para_neg_mean - siga_para_pos_mean)
    
    #start = pm.find_MAP(model=model)
    #trace = pm.sample(10000, start=start)
    v_params = pm.variational.advi(n=50000)
    trace = pm.variational.sample_vp(v_params, draws=5000)

#Fit Bayesian model of lactoferrin positivity by parasite-positive and parasite-negative groups.

with pm.Model() as model:
    para_negative_rate = pm.Uniform('para_negative_rate', lower=0, upper=1)
    lacto_positive_para_negative = pm.Binomial('lacto_positive_para_negative', len(parasite_negative_lacto.lacto_results_binary), para_negative_rate, observed=parasite_negative_lacto.lacto_results_binary.sum())
    para_positive_rate = pm.Uniform('para_positive_rate')
    lacto_positive_para_positive = pm.Binomial('lacto_positive_para_positive', len(parasite_positive_lacto.lacto_results_binary), para_positive_rate, observed=parasite_positive_lacto.lacto_results_binary.sum())
    lacto_para_neg_percent = pm.Deterministic("lacto_para_neg_percent", para_negative_rate*100)
    lacto_para_pos_percent = pm.Deterministic("lacto_para_pos_percent", para_positive_rate*100)
    diff_in_percent = pm.Deterministic("diff_in_percent", lacto_para_neg_percent - lacto_para_pos_percent)
    start = pm.find_MAP(model=model)
    trace = pm.sample(10000, start=start)

The only significant feature coefficient (p-value less than 0.05) is sIgA. Therefore, calprotectin and lactoferrin have no predictive value as to whether a sample is positive or negative for parasites. The coefficient (reported as the log of the odds that a sample is positive for parasites) for sIgA is negative, which means that the probability that a sample is positive for parasites decreases as sIgA increases. Specifically, the probability that a sample is positive for parasites decreases 0.26% per unit increase in sIgA. This agrees with the differences found in the parasite-positive and parasite-negative groups above (i.e. higher mean value of sIgA in parasite-negative group).
